comments.text: As an avid hiker who hikes and camps a lot of remote wilderness areas it's hard to believe how many people i meet 30-30 miles out who have almost no gear, no map, no compass, and no idea how to use any even if they had them. I feel so bad for these women it would be terrifying to be in their shoes. The wilderness is dangerous and you should always do your research and go prepared. Always over prepare.

comments.text: I was an Infantry solider and was sent to Panama to do jungle training for a month. We even weren't in that heavy of a jungle and trails were usually nearby.  In a deep jungle environment, forget it.  With no compass, water, food (other than a snack or two) you can die quickly in a jungle.  It must have been a lonely, terrifying death for them.  They could have easily been attacked or eaten by animals after they became exhausted.  I cant imagine just sleeping there night after night, the massive bugs, insects, strange mammals running all over the place.  God be with them.

comments.text:
I have grown up next to the Alps, you can see the Monviso from my balcony, my house is at 580 metres elevation and there's a woodland just behind, with a lot of wild boars and licensed hunters and poachers in the national park area. 

I live one hour and half (well a bit more if you drive safely) from the tallest peak in Europe, the Most Blanc, my first hike there was the summer before I started elementary school, I was six years old. We had just came back from Egypt, where we had trekked in the desert a lot and before school started, my dad took me hiking and camping at high elevation on the Mont Blanc. He's a former servicemen as are many people from my area, from the Alpine Regiment, the mountaineer military regiment, they do their basic at altitude, they are the best trackers, hikers, rock climbers with specific military training for the Alps. 

I have hiked in both Sarawak and Sabah in Borneo, I have climbed Mount Kinabalu, I have trekked in on 3 different holidays in Malaysia, I also have travelled and hiked in Indonesia, in Vietnam, twice in Thailand. 

I can tell you that. I once got lost in the woods behind my house, a place that I know like the back of my hand, a wooded area, where it gets dark quickly as that side of the hill is covered by another hill, so the sun goes down early, add to that thick vegetation. 

I was lost for five hours. FIVE hours and at no point I was more than 800 metres away from my house, I honestly thought I would not make it out alive. Luckily, I had a map, compass, a swiss army knife, an opinel knife, a hatchet, a canteen with water and one canteen with a guarana, vitamins and protein, I had a waterproof torch in my trousers, a bigger torch in my backpack, I had protein bars in my trouser pockets and other highly nutritional bars. 

I also had a spare smartphone in my bag, attached to a USB battery with four ports, fully charged. Yet both my phones had malfunctioning GPS. 

I went off trail for no more than 50 paces, jumped over a small stream, stopped to have a snack, then when I got up, I could not trace my way back to the trail. Walked for hours to the point of exhaustion. Luckily the nutrition and caffeine drink I had kept me going. 

I also made a mistake in navigating with map and compass. 


As I said I'm from the Alps, I have been trekking, hiking and camping at altitude since I'm six years old, including on the Mont Blanc at the highest level you can reach before rockclimbing, where the trees gave way to rocks. Harsh terrain. First with folks, then with my friends from the Alpine Regiment, then alone. 

Let me tell you, if the Alps can kill you in one night due to temperature drops, falls into ravines, etc.. and you can get lost and not find your trail even if you walked off it for 25 paces to relieve yourself, from my experience in Borneo and other places in Malaysia and other Southeast Asian countries, you can go off trail for five paces, stop to take a dump, and not be able to trace back where you came from. 

It is that easy. It really that easy, listen to some of the military guys here and what they say. 

Forests and jungles are unforgiving as are the mountains. Even experienced, by my standards, so veterans of the Alpine Regiment, locals who have grown up on the Alps and have twenty years of weekly hikes, ten day hikes, high elevation camping, even they succumb to the elements, either hypothermia, paradoxical undressing or simple falls. 

I never venture out without a backpack with a sleeping bag in it. 
In my pockets I carry, attached to small ropes tied to my trousers:
-One torch
-One swiss army general utility knife
-An opinel
-A compass
-proten bars

In my backpack I also carry a spare torch, a hatchet, a spare map, another compass, an extra smartphone attached to a USB battery. Plus food rations and two canteens. 

I always wear trekking shoes, never wear shorts (NEVER), always have trousers that can withstand rain and/or snow, depending on season or how how far up I'm going, always have a coat that will be good for both rain and snow and extra warm clothing. 

I read so many posts made in the comment section by Youtube "experts", who would probably struggle to find a way out of their mom's basement, making claims like "you cannot get lost on that trail"...in one case one guy was arguing against a man who had underwent jungle training in Panama in the military (down in this very comment section), can you imagine the arrogance of some basement dweller saying to this man, "no you're wrong you cannot get lost there I've watched a docu on it". How could you possibly be so arrogant to disagree with somebody who's been there and done that in the military while you ahve never been in that terrain or a similar terrain. 

WHAT? You can get lost on ANY trail, even in places you are familiar with, let alone a tropical jungle you have no knowledge of. They had only been in country for one bloody week, that's not even enough time to acclimatize.

Ten paces off trail to pee, you are about to pee against a tree when you see movement, thinking snake or spider you move away and turn, now if you retrace back your steps, you will NOT end up back in the trail as you have turned and moved. If you had stayed with your back to the trail, you could turn around and walk back. However just moving about can mean getting lost. 

Some people here going for the murder theory underestimate how bloody intense and thick a jungle is, take the woods and multiply by many measures, louder sounds, a background of wildlife noise that can be overwhelming, heat, humidity, slippery rocks, the most DENSE vegetation you can imagine. 

As I said my first two treks were at six years of age in the summer of 1990, right before starting elementary school, trekking in the desert in Egypt, followed by hiking and camping at high altitude on the Mont Blanc, on the Alps. 

I'm 37, I have decades of experience under my belt and I could easily be swallowed up by the woods that surround my house. 

Please never underestimate the outdoors.

Fact is: something must have frightened the two women so much in broad daylight that they feared to go back but continued in the opposite direction. That would also explain why the women in the pictures no longer laugh happily or stop for selfies together. Later they may have realized that this probably wasn't a good decision. Without the right equipment, in completely unknown terrain and in absolute darkness, frightened by strange, "scary" noises and your own "blooming" imagination, the first evening becomes a real nightmare. If the two young women were actually running from something or someone, then the darkness must have been horrific. It is quite possible that an accident actually happened, which would have prevented another run away and would have handed her over to a possible pursuer. It is conceivable that initially only the fallen and injured woman fell into the hands of her pursuer. The other was probably able to hide and tried to get help on her girlfriend's cell phone. That would also explain why the phone wasn't unlocked with the PIN. Whoever was the pursuer knew there were two women, so there was no way the other could survive either.
Personally, I don't think two twenty-year-old European women without any survival experience or training would think of leaving signs when they're lost in the rainforest. The deposited utensils, the backpack, the shorts, the branches arranged as signposts and the "cry for help" composed with toilet paper and a mirror therefore seem to me to be the work of professionals who have deliberately set the wrong track here. Honestly, as a "spoiled" city kid who neither knows nor understands the jungle, you're preoccupied with surviving and not with the logical thinking that comes naturally to a trained survivalist.

I'm not going to lie. As a beginner hiker I got myself into some scary situations. One time I was hiking to the top of a mountain in the middle of the city in Banff, Canada. Sounds safe enough. 
It suddenly got very foggy, and I looked up and there was no one around, everyone had left (I was busy playing with a chipmunk ).I couldn't even see the trail anymore with the deep fog, and there were so many dangerous side trails, I just kept getting on the wrong trail. I couldn't find my way down, dark was approaching, and it's bear territory, and I was alone. I was panicking, but I was lucky to still have cell service, I was about to call search and rescue, when I realized I could use Google maps to see the trail and where I'm at on it, and was able to get back on the trail. I thought I was calm in emergencies, but this time I wasn't. 

I've learned a lot of lessons the hard way. No matter how easy you THINK the hike is, always being a map, plenty of water, some food, and something for self defense. I know some people think badly of electronic maps, but preloaded alltrail maps have helped immensely. I always bring backup power for my phone as well.

If it's a longer hike, you need more, but those are the basics.

comments.text:
It is difficult to imagine how the parents and family must feel after so much speculation and absurd theories have been shaping the investigation of this case. There are two key things on this case that we should consider  if we are truly serious about finding answers and more than anything, I hope the relatives assimilate for sake of finding peace.  

First, everyone must understand how deep and profound is the mistrust between the native indigenous populations and their neighbours in the developing countries. This relationship varies between countries, but in Central America, the relationship is sometimes openly hostile between many rural indigenous communities and the westernized population.

Second, in Central America, professional, modern, skilled forensic investigation is essentially, nonexistent. I do not mean insufficient; I mean it just does not exist any shred of basic forensic science being developed and run within the people in charge. Not saying there are not many great people fully compromised with justice, I am just saying they are decades behind first world standards. 

I can assure you: there are police stations in the developing world where employees do not even know how to take a decent legible fingerprint when booking someone. Some of the people in charge of policing are not even trained! When you talk about rural areas, poor areas, like Boquete, it is even worse. Many just volunteer their time and effort to do good in their community.

Local people understand this and accept this as normal. That is the reality.
There are facts we cannot simply put aside for convenience or to fulfill likes in our you tube feed! (yes, you know who you are).
We would not be talking about this tragedy, if the girls would have stay put as soon as they realized they were lost, and if there had been a professional search and rescue team available- first thing in the morning -at the latest. 

I honestly believe, the official conclusion is correct. This was an accident but many things do not make sense simply by the fact, that the truth was not told as of when and where- the backpack was found! Why? Because no innocent indigenous person is willing to go to jail, for the sake of the Panamanian tourist industry or simply to help close a case the corrupt and incompetent authority cannot even begin to process! Simply as that! 

The indigenous Nobi are not hiding a crime. I honestly believe they had nothing, nothing to do with the disappearance, more in fact, they would have helped the girls! They simply do not trust the Police. They trust no one outside their community. Police in Panama is more than corrupt! There are no laws in Panama! (even for white collar people and multinational corporations and that is why they operate based in Panama) The indigenous would have been locked up as scapegoats just to appease the Dutch Government. Their logic is this: you found the backpack? You killed these girls. You go to jail. Case closed. Look up on the internet on how police and the government operate in Latin America. Indigenous people are not even considered third class citizens at best, and this is reality, no matter how hurtful this is. It is a real life drama.

To add to this, the Police botched up the case. As simple as that. And once again, not because they did not want to find the truth, just because police in these parts of the world have no clue on how to run a decent professional investigation. It is the sad reality. I know this, you know this.

Why do you have so many sets of fingerprints on the camera? Possibly, because there were Nobi hands all over the girls things and, because you had many hands playing with everything at the police station! Why cant you find picture 509 in the memory card? Possibly, because a wise guy at the police station deleted the file while transferring the files by accident? Or even possibly, and this may be something some people will find absurd  but  it may be true as true is that all electronics are not 100% perfect: the card was corrupted or defective and photo 509 is simply photo 510. The card could not process or execute a file titled 509. We cannot simply assume this is not possible. The family may be able to confirm this bay looking up for photo albums taken with this camera.

I venture to think photo 509 did not exist or was deleted by the police. So, when think about serial killers, a sexual predator, drug trafficking ring, human traffickerslet us get real! It is smore likely you can find one of these in your neighbourhood- or right next door -than in the middle of a jungle in Boquete. I can assure you, Boquete is safer than many neighbourhoods in big cities in Europe and North America. Many people depend on tourism and many live simple and decent lives and have no ill wish to tourists. 

What happened then? No one will know exactly what happened. I believe eventually more remains will appear, but no one will know for sure. I believe Kris and Lisanne made a few mistakes and then made a heroic and admirable intent to rectify and survive the drama. They started their hike a little late and quite possibly, assumed the trail was some kind of a loop and they continued with the hike and eventually became concerned about being lost. There was no accident, imminent danger and that is why there were only two calls that evening. They assumed they could walk out the following day. They continued to walk even farther away from Boquete.  I am sure they thought they would walk out the jungle at some point and  or be found.

So many assumptions regarding many things. The fishy guide. Why did he go to look for them? Because no party to guide meant no income for the day. They had an arrangement. That is why he went to look up for them. Why did he find the remains? Possibly because those are the trails he walks often as a guide for hikers. Who else knew those trails better than him? He did. His life has been a nightmare ever since. If someone had stalked, attacked, and killed those girls: they would have done the deed early, the phones would not have been found/ used. As simple as that.  
It has been stated the frantic photos at night clearly show intent to leave signal of a site. To pinpoint something in the case the camera was found. I believe the camera was used in a state of panic, and confusion after one of the girls passed late at night during rain fall.  The other girl quite possibly kept moving and later also passed on, not far away from where ethe pictures were taken.

I believe, the backpack was left in a ravine or somewhere safe from the rising waters and found very soon after the girls passed. The Nobi kept everything clean and dry for weeks and eventually decided to turn them in to avoid problems after hearing about the lost girls from their community. 

Something everyone seems to be concerned of: why the two bras were in the backpack? How about the shorts? Simple. See, they did not carry only -1- bottle of water. Right? You cannot assume they had only one bottle because only one bottle was found in the backpack, right? I am sure at one point, walking thru a humid and warm jungle they decided to quite possibly remove clothing as convenient and comfortable. Sometimes without the bras, only on tops and sometimes only with the bras or swim trunks.

And more importantly: I believe they carried extra clothing as they could have even tried to reach the waterfalls. They carried swimming suits. If you think about this, somethings start to make sense  at least that is my humble take. Why werent these found in the backpack? They were wearing the swimming trunks when they perished.

Kris shorts may have been found in the backpack. I could almost bet on it, but we will never know unless who ever found the things comes up clean. The shorts and the clothing may have even been used by the indigenous for a while. How couldnt we even dismiss this? 

No one, not you or me would last a week in a jungle, with no water, no food. I believe their remains simply were taken and disposed by wild animals and scattered as they moved thru their habitat.
We cannot even imagine how we would have reacted, processed reality while living this nightmare. I truly feel sad for the girls and even more for the parents. Somehow, reading so many absurd stories and people even making money out of this tragedy (yes, that is you Juan Perea) makes me feel upset and I can only hope more people could be have more objectivity while searching truth because finally, we should all be helping these families heal and have peace.

This video doesn't shed any new light or really make any surprising, new points. Also, it completely misses out information. It hardly touches on the account of how the tour guide came to ring the authorities to report that the girls were missing, for example. Most other accounts report that the tour guide 'F' (or Feliciano) got use of a key to the girls' room on the day after the girls had set out. He had spent about thirty minutes on his own in their room at lunchtime but then had not reported their absence until five o'clock that same day, the 2nd of April. Also the taxi driver's story contained certain inaccuracies. He was found drowned in a muddy puddle, presumably, murdered two years after the girls' disappearance. The only local who's mentioned a lot is that nice, trustworthy man, Plenio. Why is so much attention focussed on him? He wasn't a witness of anything in particular. If other accounts have given importance to figures like the tour-guide then this video is almost obliged to mention him even if it is only to explain away the suspicions of his guilt.
And what about that missing picture? The one that would have had to be eliminated later on a computer. 
Because so much is missed out, the video is long and rather winding and perhaps is intended to hypnotise the viewer into believing that the investigation achieved everything that it could have done and that people just have a morbid tendency to want to believe in foul play even when there are no real grounds for it. Also this video contains information that is clearly false like that the backpack had just casually been washed up onto the bank. None of the items inside the bag and indeed the bag itself had in fact shown signs of having been submerged in the river. And then the idea that Lisanne took off her shorts, neatly folded them up and left them on a rock to serve as a sign that she'd been there is quite ingenious but crazy. So what did she do? Did she continue in her underwear? On her own, in the jungle? I get the impression that this report was commissioned as a debunk video and the journalist was paid by the interested parties, the Panamanian authorities perhaps or those that make a lot of money from tourism in the area. The fact that it is quite long and lacking in content is typical of the style. If people don't make it to the end of the video, that's not a problem, the important thing is to make the gesture and to put people's minds at rest that no foul play had been involved. I don't pretend to know what really happened but I think that this video is not as objective and impartial as it seeks to appear.

comments.text: In another video, the parents of Kris Kremers took the same trail to get an idea of the terrain the young women faced months earlier. They stated that there could have been no way for the ladies to have gotten lost because thick vegetation surrounds the trail on both sides. However, I think they did not factor in the following: 1) They retraced their daughter's steps already knowing the outcome. Hindsight is always viewed with 20/20 glasses; 2) The parents had guides with them and could have never gotten lost, whereas Kris and Lisanne were unguided and unfamiliar with the area; 3) Having hiked countless trails in many countries (including tropical ones) myself, there is always the main trail but animal trails and washes that look like trails, many single-track and narrow, are always present. It would be easy for inattentive newbies talking and snapping photos to start walking along one of these by mistake; 4) Kris's parents took a day trip and brought the necessary gear and supplies, but as we know based on the calls that were made on Kris and Lisanne's phones, that the two were out there for days with insufficient food and clothing. People have commented that they could have simply walked out. Seemed like Kris had gotten injured and Lisanne could not, or did not want, to leave her. With each passing day, the lack of food and exposure to the elements would have taken a toll on them mentally and physically. Other thoughts: Why did they take night shots of seemingly random things? Jungles come alive at night. I'd be doing the same thing if there were things moving around and making sounds in the darkness. Why did they call 112 (the equivalent of 911) in the Netherlands? My guess is because it was familiar to them. They had not been in Panama for very long after all and would have known that calling their homeland's emergency agency would have been more reliable than calling the hostel where they were staying. The Dutch responders would have immediately known to contact their parents to make them aware of the situation. Of course the rest of this tragic story raises more questions than answers and has many parts, but this is just my take about one of those parts.
